MARKET UPDATE

Impact of coronavirus on investment strategy

The developments of the coronavirus epidemic in South Korea, Japan, Iran an=
d especially Italy caused the markets to react strongly on Monday. Global i=
ndices are in the red with for example -3.9% for the Korean Kospi index and=
 -3.8% in Europe at the time of writing. Safe haven stocks have continued e=
nd of last week trend, with the US 10-year yield reaching 1.39%, close to a=
n all-time low, while the Bund is at -0.50%. Gold continues to rise and is =
trading around $1675/oz. In response to investors' stress, implied volatili=
ties rose sharply to over 20%. Our options strategies are now above their i=
nitial purchase price.

The contagion to Europe has led our Global Investment Committee to meet exc=
eptionally today to discuss our strategy and positioning. Fears of recessio=
n due to a possible shutdown of activity are the main cause of this sharp d=
ecline across markets. Indeed, precautionary quarantine measures similar to=
 those imposed in China raise fears of a strong economic impact at a time w=
hen European economic growth is weak and therefore vulnerable. It is import=
ant to note that this correction comes after a strong period of market appr=
eciation and that valuations are above their historical average. While the =
markets may have the potential for a correction in the short term, we are a=
lready 5% below the recent high of the Eurostoxx index. It should also be n=
oted that bond markets have reacted more strongly than equities, showing a =
divergence of views that could only need to be corrected.

In the longer term, we will have to assess the impact on economic growth an=
d on corporate earnings, which in the current state of affairs appears a pe=
rilous exercise given the lack of hindsight and the ongoing developments of=
 the epidemic. Undoubtedly, the interest rate and liquidity environment can=
 only remain hyper-accommodating, which will provide some support for asset=
 prices. But in a supply shock, the support of demand presents the risk of =
being initially inoperative. In other words, the question is whether we are=
 facing a structural shock affecting demand and supply, or a transitory phe=
nomenon that would lead to a rapid V-shaped recovery that does not call int=
o question our investment scenario. Economic and corporate earnings publica=
tions will therefore be particularly closely monitored in the weeks and mon=
ths ahead!

On the other hand, and in line with our expectations, Chinese activities se=
em to be picking up, suggesting that the worst is now behind us. Central ba=
nk support remains important and should continue to be provided given the l=
ack of visibility. The inflow of liquidity therefore provides a floor for t=
he indices and could lead to a buy-the-dip attitude in the short term, alth=
ough this remains to be seen. Against this backdrop, European equities seem=
 more vulnerable to us.

Our recommendations for portfolios are as follows:

=A7  Reduce our exposure to European equities and reallocate to US equities,

=A7  Maintain a neutral equity stance and maintain protective strategies (e=
.g. put options strategies and EdR Solve),

=A7  Maintain allocations in safe haven assets such as Swiss francs, US dol=
lars, government bonds (US) and tactically increase the exposure gold expos=
ure.

The Investment Committee continues to monitor the situation closely and doe=
s not rule out further adjustments to our positioning in the coming days/we=
eks.


